5. Advantages of Docker compose.
- Yes, Docker Compose is used in lower environments.
We had a microservice-based application with a Node.js backend, a PostgreSQL database, and Redis for caching.Instead of running each service manually, I defined them in a docker-compose.yml file. (Note: this can be done with cmds as welll, but to perform in a structured way , we are using compose file, reduces manual effort)

--- Docker Compose is useful because it lets you define and run multi-container applications with a single configuration file. It simplifies setup, ensures consistency across environments, and makes scaling services easier. In my project, I used Docker Compose to run a Node.js backend, PostgreSQL, and Redis together. This saved time during development and testing since the whole stack could be started with one command. For production, we later moved to Kubernetes, but Docker Compose was invaluable for local development and CI pipelines.
Advantages:
Multi-container orchestration: Easily define and run multiple services (e.g., app, database, cache) with one command.
Simplified configuration: Uses a single docker-compose.yml file to describe services, networks, and volumes.
Portability: Same configuration works across environments (local dev, staging, CI/CD).
Isolation: Each service runs in its own container, avoiding dependency conflicts.
Easy scaling: Can scale services up/down with simple commands.

